(875, 1, '2012-09-21 07:44:24', '2012-09-21 14:44:24', 'The cooler months mean the heaters are about to come on.  When this happens they tend to pull moisture out of the air, making fall and winter the worst times for dry skin.  Conditions like eczema, atopic dermatitis, psoriasis, and seborrheic dermatitis tend to flare up at this time of year.  Some basic dry skin care steps are outlined below.  The first 7 are good general principles most people can benefit from, the last few items are for people with the most severe dryness.\r\n\r\n1. Use moisturizers such as Vanicream (<a title="Vanicream" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/products-page/moisturizer/vanicream/">BUY NOW</a>), best for people with very sensitive skin, or Cerave (<a title="CeraVe Cream" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/products-page/moisturizer/cerave-cream/">BUY NOW</a>) a more general purpose slightly lighter cream, Eucerin cream, Cetaphil cream, Aquaphor or Vaseline petroleum jelly several times a day, especially after bathing or washing to lock-in moisture.  In general creams are better than lotions.\r\n2. Use very little soap, and only in areas needed. Use a mild soap such as Dove sensitive skin bar soap.  If your skin is very dry, Cetaphil cleanser is an alternative to Dove soap.\r\n3. Do Not vigorously scrub with a washcloth, sponge, or brush.\r\n4. Reduce bathing time to 5 minutes, and always apply a moisturizer immediately after bathing.\r\n5. Use lukewarm water-avoid hot or cold water.\r\n6. After bathing or washing, PAT your skin with a towel to dry gently.\r\n7. Do not use bubble bath.\r\n8. Do not use colognes, perfumes, sprays, powders etc. on your skin.\r\n9. Use unscented laundry products- both detergents and fabric softeners. If dry skin or inflammation persists with lubrication or prescription medication, you can also double rinse clothes after washing.\r\n10. Prescription creams and ointments should be applied to affected areas. Moisturizers are best applied at different times: if applied at the same time as prescription ointments or creams, always apply the prescription medication first.\r\n11. Do not wear tight or rough clothing. Wool clothes and new clothes can be irritating.\r\n12. Avoid saunas and steam baths\r\n13. For extreme dryness, a humidifier or vaporizer may help. Remember to keep it clean or molds may spread throughout the humidified area.', 'Dry Skin in the Fall and Winter', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dry-skin-in-the-fall-and-winter', '', '', '2012-09-21 07:44:24', '2012-09-21 14:44:24', '', 0, 'http://www.pacedermatology.com/?p=875', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(867, 2, '2012-09-11 18:59:33', '2012-09-12 01:59:33', 'Having a healthy and stable skin care routine is one of the best ways to help reduce acne flare-ups. The American Academy of Dermatology has seven tips that have been recommended by dermatologists to help care for acne prone skin.  If you skin does not respond to these basic steps please consider making an appointment with a dermatologist.\r\n\r\n1. Make sure to wash twice a day and after sports or sweating.\r\n\r\n2. Always wash your face gently using your fingertips and with a non-abrasive cleanser.  Salicylic acid and benzoyl peroxide cleansers are often quite effective.  Acne scrubs are generally not recommended more than once a week.\r\n\r\n3. Water temperature is not critical, but rinsing with lukewarm water is probably best.\r\n\r\n4. If you have oily hair, make sure you shampoo regularly since areas where it touches your face will be especially prone to acne breakouts.\r\n\r\n5. Do not pick at acne lesions.  Letting your skin heal naturally is faster and lessens the chance of permanent scarring.\r\n\r\n6. Keeping your hands off your face will reduce break-outs.\r\n\r\n7. Limit sun exposure and always avoid tanning booths!\r\n\r\nRead more from the <a href="http://www.aad.org/stories-and-news/news-releases/want-clearer-skin-reduce-acne-by-following-these-top-tips-from-dermatologists">American Academy of Dermatology</a>', 'Dermatologist Recommended Tips for Clearer Skin', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dermatologist-recommended-tips-for-clearer-skin', '', '', '2012-09-11 18:59:33', '2012-09-12 01:59:33', '', 0, 'http://www.pacedermatology.com/?p=867', 0, 'post', '', 0),
