(1035, 1, '2012-10-13 17:11:51', '2012-10-14 00:11:51', '<h1><strong>Nd:YAG for Vascular Lesions</strong></h1>\nNeodymium:Yttrium Aluminum Garnet (Nd:YAG) laser for vascular lesions is highly effective.  The laser energy is absorbed by the vessel which coagulates the vessel causing it to collapse. The body absorbs the vessel over a period of several weeks. Often a series of 4-6 treatments are required to completely eliminate the vessels. The downtime is minimal.  It can be used for a range of vascular lesions including telangiectasias, cherry angiomas, and leg veins.\n\n<strong>Leg Veins</strong>\nYou will not be required to wear support stockings after treatments but it is generally recommend as it will slow the formation of new leg veins. You should not to exercise for the first 48 hours after treatment and avoid long hot showers, sauna, steam rooms and hot tubs. The treatment is tolerated well by most people. Once again you will be advised to avoid sun exposure to the treated area for one month prior and post treatment to avoid pigment issues. Our providers will assist you with a consultation and developing a treatment plan for you.  The combination Nd:YAG therapy allows treatment of many leg veins that previous had to be injected using sclerotherapy. Benefits over traditional sclerotherapy include that laser is fast, less painful; minimally invasive without needles; and typically does not require compression wrapping.\n\n<strong>Telangiectasias and Cherry Angiomas</strong>\nNd:YAG technology provides multiple synchronized pulsing to selectively heat blood vessels of different sizes and depths. The wavelength of light and pulsing characteristics of the system allow the energy to be virtually invisible to the epidermal melanin, thus protecting the skin. Normally only a few pulses of the laser are required to achieve complete closure and sealing of the vessels. The sapphire cooled Nd:YAG treatment head increases patient comfort and safety. Multiple spot sizes available allows accurate targeting of vessels anywhere on the body including larger telangiectasia on the face and ang\n\nQ: How does high-tech laser/light technology compare to traditional sclerotherapy?\n\nA: The combined light sources of IPL and Nd:YAG offer important benefits over injection therapy.\n\nVascular and Pigmented Lesions\n\nQ: What product solutions are available to treat vascular lesions?\n\nA: Depending on the specific nature of the condition, Lumenis offers two key solutions for the treatment of benign vascular lesions. The Lumenis One Nd:YAG successfully treats a broad range of vascular conditions including telangiectasia, , hemangiomas, etc.  Deeper vascular lesions can be treated with our Nd:YAG laser systems available on the IPL Lumenis One.', 'Laser Vein Removal', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1034-revision', '', '', '2012-10-13 17:11:51', '2012-10-14 00:11:51', '', 1034, 'http://www.pacedermatology.com/1034-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1037, 1, '2012-10-13 16:09:01', '2012-10-13 23:09:01', '<h1><strong>Laser Hair Removal</strong></h1>\r\nCall (253) 572-2842 to book a consult and get ready to say goodbye to shaving, waxing, tweezing and electrolysis with laser hair removal.\r\n\r\n<strong>How many Treatments?</strong>\r\nMost people benefit from a series of 4-6 treatments, spaced at six to eight weeks apart. After the initial series of treatments, the hair in a given area is usually reduced in both amount and thickness for a long period of time. In order to keep an area completely devoid of hair, maintenance treatments are almost always required.  Areas that can be treated include the upper lip, chin, cheeks, underarms, bikini, arms, legs and back.\r\n\r\n<strong>Am I a Candidate for Laser Hair Removal?</strong>\r\nBoth men and women may seek laser hair removal services to have unwanted hair removed. Hair removal is commonly done on the hairline, eyebrow, top of nose, lip, chin, underarm, abdomen, buttocks, pubic area, bikini lines, thighs, face, neck, breast, arms, legs, hands, and toes. Laser on pale skin and dark coarse hair. The closer you are to this combination the better your results will generally be.\r\n\r\n<strong>Is Laser Hair Removal Permanent?</strong>\r\nYou shouldn’t expect the laser to remove every single hair from the area. Most people return for follow up treatments 1-2 times a year after the initial set of treatments for any new growth your body develops with age. Factors that determine the length of treatment include the particular area to be treated, the texture of hair, frequency of treatment, and history of temporary measures to remove hair; waxing, tweezing, shaping, and depilatories, etc. Laser hair removal can also partially treat an area if only a reduction in the number of hairs is desired.  This can be achieved with having only a few treatments instead of the complete set.\r\n\r\n<strong>What should I Expect Before Treatment?</strong>\r\nYou should shave the area that is to be treated before treatment. Avoid plucking, waxing, and electrolysis for 4-6 weeks prior to procedure as hair needs to be in place to be targeted by the laser. The area should be shaved as closely as possible so that laser can target the most energy towards the hair follicle and not waste energy on the part of the hair above the skin’s surface. You should avoid sun to the area prior to and after treatment to prevent hyper pigmentation following the procedure.\r\n\r\n<strong>Is Laser Hair Removal Painful?</strong>\r\nEveryone’s pain tolerance is different, but generally laser hair removal is not much more painful than waxing, but the sensation is different. In one pulse, the laser can remove all the hair on a patch of skin the size of a nickel. The sensation of the laser resembles a rubber band snapping against the skin for a quick second with each pulse. Most people do not require an anesthetic cream but one may be used for very sensitive patients/areas. Using anesthetic cream is only safe on small areas (upper lip, bikini, or underarms) and in small quantities.\r\n\r\n<strong>What should I Expect After Treatment?</strong>\r\nAfter treatment is completed your skin may feel irritated. The treated area will be pink and slightly swollen immediately following treatment. A mild topical steroid such as otc hydrocortisone can be used to soothe the skin for a few days. Within 2-3 weeks you should experience shedding of all treated hair. You should experience a hair free period for a few weeks, until the hair cycles into the growth phase. On average, this occurs in 6-8 weeks. When you have enough hair to justify another treatment, schedule an appointment.\r\n\r\n<strong>What are the Possible Risks and Side Effects for Laser Hair Removal?</strong>\r\nNormal side effects include itching during treatment, redness or swelling for up to three days, pain, tingling, or feeling of numbness. There are a few rare side effects that can also occur such as crusting or scabbing, formation of ingrown hairs, bruising, hyper or hypo pigmentation, viral or bacterial infection. Side effects occur infrequently and are generally temporary. If any of the effects listed last more than three days, make sure to contact your technician or physician. There is possibility that the settings were set too high and they will need to know in order to adjust on your following treatment.\r\n\r\n<strong>How much does laser hair removal cost?</strong>\r\nPrices range from $150 to $600 per treatment session depending on the location being treated.\r\n\r\n<strong>What are some Advantages of the Light Sheer Diode?</strong>\r\nThe diode laser allows the physician or nurse practioner to treat patients faster and more comfortably than other methods. It has unparalleled treatment efficacy in hair removal, especially thinner, finer hairs other hair removal lasers simply cannot touch. Sapphire contact cooling protects the skin making the procedure as safe as possible.  The diode laser is also capable of treating the broadest range of skin and hair types.\r\n\r\n<strong>Laser hair removal may be contraindicated in patients with the following:</strong>\r\n• Active Skin Infection\r\n• History of Psoriasis, Vitiligo, Frequent Herpes Infections\r\n• Tanned Skin\r\n• Accutane within 1 year', 'Laser Hair Removal', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1022-revision-5', '', '', '2012-10-13 16:09:01', '2012-10-13 23:09:01', '', 1022, 'http://www.pacedermatology.com/1022-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1038, 1, '2012-10-13 17:46:55', '2012-10-14 00:46:55', 'Call (253) 572-2842 or click on the book and appointment button to the right to book a free consult and get ready to say hello to a more youthful, natural, and brighter skin.\n\n<strong>What can it do?</strong>\nIntense Pulse Light (IPL) is the preferred method for the photofacial, a non-abrasive and less-invasive rejuvenation of your skin using the remarkable IPL technology.  It also works great for age spots, dyschromia, uneven pigment, rosacea, redness, capillaries, hair removal, and wrinkles.  IPL emits a non-coherent, broad-spectrum light. IPL Photofacials can improve the signs of sun damage, rosacea and brown spots on the face, hands, chest, and body. It has also been used to reduce the appearance of mild acne scars and fine lines around the eyes and mouth. Usually 4-6 treatment sessions lasting about 15-20 minutes each will provide you with long lasting beautiful results. There is little recuperation time, typically you can return to work or resume your normal activities on the same day. You will notice a gradual, natural-looking improvement in your skin with time. IPL is a safe solution tailor-made to your skin type and condition and thus requires a consult to scheduled treatments.\n\n<strong>Does Laser Treatment Hurt?</strong>\nWe ensure the least amount of discomfort during your procedure with cooling gel and a SapphireCool tip. We may begin treatment with a numbing agent. Many patients compare the sensation to that of a thin rubber band or pinching sensation. Generally patients find treatments very tolerable.\n\n<strong>Who does the treatments?</strong>\nAll IPL treatments are preformed experienced medical professionals.  Our nurse practitioner, <a title="Shelley Velickoff, ARNP" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/about/the-providers/shelley-velickoff-arnp/">Shelley Velickoff, ARNP</a>, provides most of the treatments under the supervision of a board certified dermatologist.  Many laser centers you laser tech or registered nurses to perform these complex procedures.  Also unlike other laser centers we provide a personalized approach based on your skin and will make sure your treatments are safe and effective.\n\n<strong>How often can treatments be done?</strong>\nFor most patients, 4-6 treatments spaced about 4 weeks apart are recommended for the most significant results.\n\n<strong>What are the side effects?</strong>\nA small amount of flushing, or redness will follow the treatment and generally lasts from 30 minutes to several hours, but in some cases may last a few days.  The brown spots and uneven pigmentation will become slightly raised and darker over the next 3-5 days.  The pigment will “slough off” within 7-10 days post treatment.  Blisters can occur, but are uncommon.  Smoother, softer skin and improvement in uneven pigmentation can be expected within weeks.\n\n<strong>How much does it cost?</strong>\nPrices vary by locations and size of area to be treated.  The range is $150-$600 per session.  Usually 4-6 sessions are needed, one exception to this is brown spots which often require fewer treatment sessions.\n\n<strong>Age Spots/Uneven Pigmentation</strong>\nAlso called liver spots and solar lentigines — are flat, brown or black spots. They vary in size and usually appear on the face, hands, shoulders and arms — areas most exposed to the sun. Though age spots are very common in adults older than age 40, they can affect younger people as well.  IPL treatment is generally very effective at removing age, liver, sun or brown spots on the skin. It is the treatment of choice for these spots.  In fact significant response may be seen in as little as two sessions, but do allow for up to six treatments.  In general we find that laser removal of age spots is long lasting but not permanent, people do sometimes see new spots appear as they go back out into the sun.  Often we recommend some of <a title="Products Page" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/products-page/">our products</a> before, during or after your treatments to promote or maintain results. These are new spots are usual forming as a result of sun exposure, not a recurrence of the old, removed spots. Good sun-avoidance is key if you wish to see your skin free of sun spots. We recommend strict sunscreen and hat usage to maintain your results.\n\n<strong>Redness/Rosacea/Capillaries</strong>\nIPL treats multiple skin conditions because it works at multiple wavelengths which target blood vessels. That means that while the IPL is treating age spots it will also reach those broken capillaries we see on our nose, cheeks and other areas. IPL does not treat or remove the deeper feeder vessels, instead the IPL will reach the red blood cells in the superficial blood vessels.  The blood vessels can appear again and we recommend returning for repeat treatment as needed in order to keep the desired results.\n\n<strong>Wrinkles</strong>\nIPL can cause an improvement in the fine lines and wrinkles.  Although some improvement can be seen we generally recommend neuromodulators like <a title="Cosmetic" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/services/cosmetic/">Botox or Dysport</a> in combination with <a title="Cosmetic" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/services/cosmetic/">fillers</a> such as Restalyne and Juvederm, as well as a series of chemical peels.  As you grow older, your skin gets thinner, drier and less elastic. And it becomes less able to protect itself from damage. As a result, wrinkles, lines and creases form in your skin. Although genetics are the most important determiner of skin texture, a major contributor to wrinkles is spending too much time in the sun. Smoking also can cause premature aging of your skin. Because IPL is helping to create new collagen, once results have been achieved you can expect them to be subtle but long lasting.  We always recommend an SPF of 30 to be worn daily.\n\n<strong>Hair Removal</strong>\nGenerally we use the <a title="Laser Hair Removal" href="http://www.pacedermatology.com/services/laser-hair-removal/">diode laser</a> for hair removal, however people with light skin and dark hair may be ideal candidates for IPL hair removal.  The decision of which device to use will be made at your consult.  Patients can expect a 75 to 80% decrease in overall hair in areas treated.  For best results patients will need to come in every 6-8 weeks. This is due to natural hair growth. Hair growth happens in cycles and treatment needs to occur while the hair is actively growing to be most effective.', 'IPL Skin Rejuvenation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1028-autosave', '', '', '2012-10-13 17:46:55', '2012-10-14 00:46:55', '', 1028, 'http://www.pacedermatology.com/1028-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
